## 1. `strncpy` zero-fill bug in `process_engine_output` (real, measurable waste)

```c
strncpy(engine_pv, ptr + 4, sizeof(engine_pv) - 1);
```

`engine_pv` is `char[1024]`. `strncpy` **pads the entire remaining destination with `\0`** when the source is shorter than `n` — which it almost always is (PVs are usually tens to a couple hundred bytes). This means every single `info ... pv ...` line (and Stockfish can emit these very frequently, especially at higher depths or with short move-time controls) zero-fills ~800–900 bytes for no reason. This is the one genuinely wasteful hot-ish path in the file. Fix:

```c
size_t l = strlen(ptr + 4);
if (l >= sizeof(engine_pv)) l = sizeof(engine_pv) - 1;
memcpy(engine_pv, ptr + 4, l);
engine_pv[l] = '\0';
```

## 2. Full `sync` barrier where `lwsync` (or nothing) suffices

```c
__sync_synchronize(); // PPC lwsync   <-- comment is aspirational, not accurate
```

`__sync_synchronize()` on GCC/PPC lowers to a full `sync` instruction (heavyweight, drains the store queue and orders all memory ops system-wide), not `lwsync`. For a classic SPSC ring buffer you only need a **release** fence on the producer before publishing `head`, and an **acquire** fence on the consumer before reading `data[]`. On Broadway (single core, no SMP), you likely don't even need a hardware fence at all — a *compiler* barrier (`asm volatile("" ::: "memory")`) is enough to stop reordering, since there's no other core to race with. If you want to be safe against DMA/cache-related surprises, use `asm volatile("lwsync" ::: "memory")` explicitly instead of the builtin. This is called on **every** `fifo_read`/`fifo_write`, including the per-character reads in `engine_fgets`/`engine_getline`, so it's the most frequently executed "expensive" instruction in the whole file.

## 3. `draw_ui()` — one `vsnprintf` per board square

```c
